    \begin{tabular}{l ccc}
        \toprule[1.5pt]
        Datasets & EG & $\alpha$NLG & SEG
         \\
        \midrule[1pt]
        Coverage & 78.4\% & 80.4\% & 43.5\% \\
        Avg. \# Concepts & 193.1 & 201.6 & 208.5 \\
        Avg. \# Triples & 1094.3 & 1324.6 & 1148.6 \\
        \bottomrule[1.5pt]
    \end{tabular}
    \caption{Statistics of the extracted subgraphs on the training sets of three datasets, including the coverage of concepts in the ground-truth target sequence, the average number of concepts and triples for each subgraph.}
    \label{tab:subgraph-stats}
\end{table}

\subsection{Hyper-parameter Setting}\label{apdx:hyperparams}

We present the detailed setting of hyper-parameters of our model on each task including hyper-parameter search space in Table \ref{tab:search} and the best configuration of hyper-parameters in Table \ref{tab:hyperparam}. 
The number of hyper-parameter search trials for each dataset is 30. We use the BLEU score on the development set as the selection criterion and utilize manual tuning~\citep{dodge19showyourwork} to select the best hyper-parameters.

\begin{table}[h]
    \centering
    \small
    \begin{tabular}{lc}
    \toprule[1.5pt]
        Hyper-parameter & Search space \\
    \midrule[1pt]
        learning rate & \{2e-4, 1e-4, 5e-5, 1e-5\} \\
        batch size & \{32, 16, 8\} \\
        \# epochs & \{5,4,3\} \\
        $\alpha$ & \{7,5,3\} \\
        $\beta$ & \{7,5,3\} \\
        $\gamma$ & \{1.0, 0.8, 0.6, 0.5, 0.4, 0.2, 0.0\} \\
    \bottomrule[1.5pt]
    \end{tabular}
    \caption{Hyper-parameter search space of GRF on three text-generation tasks.}
    \label{tab:search}
\end{table}


\begin{table}[h]
    \centering
    \small
    \begin{tabular}{l ccc}
        \toprule[1.5pt]
        Datasets & EG & $\alpha$NLG & SEG
         \\
        \midrule[1pt]
        learning rate & $2\times 10^{-4}$ & $1\times 10^{-4}$ & $1\times 10^{-4}$ \\
        batch size & 16 & 16 & 16 \\
        \# epochs & 3 & 5 & 5 \\
        $\alpha$ & 7 & 7 & 7\\
        $\beta$ & 5 & 5 & 5\\
        $\gamma$ & 0.5 & 0.5 & 0.5 \\
        \bottomrule[1.5pt]
    \end{tabular}
    \caption{Best hyper-parameters searched on the development sets of different datasets. }
    \label{tab:hyperparam}
\end{table}

\subsection{Cases}\label{apdx:cases}

We provide cases comparing our model with different baselines on three tasks. Table \ref{tab:semeval} shows three test cases of the explanation generation task. We highlight the key mentions in the generated sentences that provide reasonable information to the explanation. For example in the third case, GRF generates ``soft'' that explains why a blanket cannot be cut up while other models do not generate reasonable explanations. 

Table \ref{tab:story} shows three test cases of the story ending generation task. We highlight the key words in the generated sentences that make a reasonable story ending by following the narrative flow of the story. For example in the second case, GRF generates ``expensive'' which is the antonym of ``cheap'' in the story context while other models only generate general words such as ``new'' which is less consistent with the context. 

Table \ref{tab:anlg} shows three test cases of the abductive NLG task. We highlight key words in the generated sentences that plausibly explain the two observations. For example in the first example, GRF generates ``seasick'' which explains what bad experience the family had on the cruise, while other models either do not convey this negative information or generate general hypothesis.

\begin{table*}[h]
    \centering
    \small
    \begin{tabular}{l l}
    \toprule[1.5pt]
        \textbf{Statement \#1} & \textit{Coke} is made of \textit{alcohol}.\\
    \midrule[1pt]
        GRF & Coke is made from \textbf{corn}. \\
        GPT2-FT & Coke is a drink. \\
        GPT2-OMCS-FT & Coke is not a liquid. \\
    \midrule[1pt]
        \textbf{Statement \#2} & The average \textit{weight} of a newborn baby is 20 \textit{inches}. \\
    \midrule[1pt]
        GRF & The average weight of a newborn baby is 5 \textbf{pounds}. \\
        GPT2-FT & Babies are born weighing less than 20 inches. \\
        GPT2-OMCS-FT & The average weight of a newborn baby is 21 inches. \\
    \midrule[1pt]
        \textbf{Statement \#3} & She \textit{cut} up a \textit{blanket}. \\
    \midrule[1pt]
        GRF & Blankets are too \textbf{soft} to be cut. \\
        GPT2-FT & A blanket is not sharp enough to cut. \\
        GPT2-OMCS-FT & A blanket is too small to be cut. \\
    \bottomrule[1.5pt]
    \end{tabular}
    \caption{Test cases of the explanation generation task. Counter-factual concept pairs in the statement are shown in \textit{italics}. \textbf{Boldfaced words} in the generated sentences denote the key concepts that make a reasonable explanation.}
    \label{tab:semeval}
\end{table*}

\begin{table*}[h]
    \centering
    \small
    \begin{tabular}{l l}
    \toprule[1.5pt]
        \multirow{4}{*}{\textbf{Story Context \#1}} & Feeling parched, I made my way to the kitchen. \\
        {} & I opened a cabinet to grab a \textit{glass}. \\
        {} & I added ice and \textit{lemon} slices. \\
        {} & Then, I \textit{poured} fresh spring water into my \textit{glass}.\\
    \midrule[1pt]
        GRF & I \textbf{drank} the \textbf{lemonade} and felt much better. \\
        GPT2-FT & I \underline{poured} the lemon into the glass and \textbf{drank} it. \\
        GPT2-OMCS-FT & Finally, I \underline{poured} lemon into the glass. \\
        IE+GA & i was the water and then the glass. \\
    \midrule[1pt]    
        \multirow{4}{*}{\textbf{Story Context \#2}} & I wanted a simple bike for commuting. \\
        {} & So I bought a \textit{cheap} one on sale. \\
        {} & But it didn't fit me properly. \\
        {} & And it was uncomfortable to ride. \\
    \midrule[1pt]
        GRF & So I decided to get a more \textbf{expensive} bike. \\
        GPT2-FT & So I decided to buy a new bike. \\
        GPT2-OMCS-FT & So I decided to buy a bike from a bike shop instead. \\
        IE+GA & so i decided to buy a new one. \\
    \midrule[1pt]
        \multirow{4}{*}{\textbf{Story Context \#3}} & Ava made chocolate shakes for her kids on a \textit{hot} summer day. \\
        {} & She called them in from play, but they dallied. \\
        {} & By time they came in, the shakes were almost \textit{melted.} \\
        {} & Ava blended in more \textit{ice} cubes and refreshed them. \\
    \midrule[1pt]
    
        GRF & Her kids thanked her profusely for helping them \textbf{cool} off. \\
        GPT2-FT & Ava was proud of her kids for being so good at cooking. \\
        GPT2-OMCS-FT & She was proud of her kids for being so thoughtful! \\
        IE+GA & then she went home and ate them. \\ 
        
    \bottomrule[1.5pt]
    \end{tabular}
    \caption{Test cases of the story ending generation task. \textit{Italics} denote the salient concepts in the story context. \textbf{Boldfaced words} in the generated sentences denote the key concepts that follow the narrative flow of the story. \underline{Underlined texts} are inconsistent descriptions with regard to the story context.}
    \label{tab:story}
\end{table*}

